<br>
The post by Mossiah fails because it lists changes in gross tax revenues versus some more reliable relative measure. Absolute measures can never tell the story of whether expected revenues have adjusted and reached expected values that justify causal claims such as those made by supplysiders. <br>
<br>
For example, I can claim that holding the line on state Tax increases in Texas have resulted in increased tax revenues for the School district in which I am employed. I could point to &quot;empirical evidence&quot; such that the state funded portion of the school district budget went up 18 million dollars( which it in fact has). So, has holding the line on taxes increased revenues? <br>
<br>
Yes in absolute terms. Definitively NO if we take the slightest bit of energy and look further into how agencies, bureaus, programs, school districts, etc are funded. If we note that four NEW schools were opened in the district this year we note that due to the SIGNIFICANT increase in student population that per last year's expenditure\state funding level per student, revenues to keep pace would had to go up three times what they did in absolute terms in order to just STAY the SAME on a relative scale. <br>
<br>
But I understand Ammelen that your political agenda is to defund government wherever it exist and I will grant that reliance on absolute measures is a good tact to assume given that pursuit. <br>
<br>
Honestly, speaking from a purely academic vantage point, I would argue that the impact of gov't spending\taxation on overall prosperity (GNP) is overrated. These tax policy issues have little to do with overall economic welfare or GNP and much MORE to do with distribution of wealth issues. However, the foregoing political agenda likes to frame tax policy as a GNP issue or one having to do with overall prosperity. <br>
<br>
I think much more compelling is the impact of Federal Reserve monetary policy. Yet even there, along with Milton Friedman's meandering about &quot;only money matters&quot; we had to swallow a fair dose of politicalization of economic policy that had more to do with distribution issues than with prosperity. <br>
<br>
There is certainly no one &quot;right&quot; school of economics. Otherwise we could just shut down every school of economics in the country and just place all the &quot;edicts of economic righteousness&quot; in a textbook and be done with the business of teaching the next generation of economist and political leaders how to weigh the very contentious issues that come up with this type of debate. <br>
<br>
John Maynard Keyes said something that shines some wisdom on the dangers of buying into the politicized vagueries of the favored &quot;economic theory of the day&quot; :<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The ideas of economists and political philosophers, both when they are right and when they are wrong, are more powerful than is commonly understood. Indeed the world is ruled by little else. Practical men, who believe themselves to be quite exempt from any intellectual influence, are usually the slaves of some defunct economist. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Fullscale &quot;buying in&quot; to supplyside economics or the extreme on the left, is a road to nowhere....<br>
<br>
