<br>
The quintessential dynamic at work is no different than it was for Henry Ford around the turn of the century where he determined that advances in productivity in producing automobiles allowed him to produce at a lower cost and pay a much higher nominal wage than his competition. In fact, many in his industry at that time thought he would be bankrupt within 5 years because they subscribed to a school of business\economic not that far outta sync with what I hear from supplysiders these days. <br>
<br>
Obviously, and what any first MBA student will tell you, is that such dour forecast did not materialize and Ford dominated the auto industry until the depression when GM took over for reasons not related to the point at hand. <br>
<br>
The point to be noted here is simply that both sides of the economic equation need to be balanced. You cannot construct prosperity by simply isolating your policy on supplyside inputs. Demand side issues are every bit as important. Henry Ford took the lead in his day and saw the value of finding a way to produce for less and pay his workers more so that they could become consumers of his product. <br>
<br>
Who will be the person in this day and age who will come forward and do the same? I don't know, but Arthur Laffer, Ronald Reagan, and the subsequent ilk of the supplyside mantra are going down an entirely wrongheaded path. <br>
<br>
These individuals of the political right are nothing more than handmaidens of the ultra rich designated to pursue a political policy carefully cloaked in sheep's costume of a &quot;new economic theory of prosperity&quot; of defunding Government at all levels irregardless of what the ballot box has said in support of some very successful governmental programs. These people do not trust the majority. For that reason their antidemocratic butts need to be thrown out.  <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=626910" target="top">Chopstiks Kungfoey</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1795<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/15/03 12:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: supply side economics</span><hr size=1> There is a very strong inverse correlation between growth and tax rates.  It's not arguable, it's math.  Your argument that technology increases productivity is certainly true, but that is monotonic.  Our technology continues to improve, yet we don't always experience the same growth, and we do experience recessions.  Mathematically, growth is tied to a large extent to tax rates.<br>
<br>
It's quite simple logic really.  People work harder when they keep more of their money, increasing total productivity, and increasing the tax base.  Thus it increases revenues and fuels the economy.  This is beyond obvious to me.<br>
<br>
Most liberals will even acknowledge that cutting taxes causes economic growth, they simply argue that the revenue loss incurred by cutting rates does not balance the revenue gain from the increased tax base, thus the government's total net revenues go down.  This is sometimes true.  However, that does not change the fact that lower tax rates give greater productivity.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=truthreason>TruthReason</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1388<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/15/03 2:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=171.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: supply side economics</span><hr size=1> That all real economic growth is directly the result of productivity increases is beginner material in most schools of general economics(which I might add are filled with professors with a decidely conservative bent). In my case it was pounded home in third and fourth semester Macro\Micro economics sequence. <br>
<br>
Productivity differences are what lies behind comparative advantage theory (this undergirds the free trade argument...hail, nafta) <br>
<br>
I'm not really bragging about this, but I know the subject, I have a degree in economics(from top 20 school of general economics), I taught economics as a paid tutor in college(5 years) and again in high school for five years. I see the nuances and I see where supplysiders have made theoretic inroads which are very welcomed, but conversely I see where alot of their positions on the relationship between taxes and revenues is purely politically motivated fiction. I'm truly a moderate in terms of which theory I subscribe to because I think that is where the truth lies. <br>
<br>
Also, I might mention that(if you are even marginally interested in reading in the subject area) public choice theory has been an emerging subfield of economics where they have done some amazing work on quantifying and theoretically representing how the public can rationally choose through market mechanisms to &quot;purchase&quot; a certain amount of government generated public goods. Cool stuff....taking externalities and putting them into a macro economic perspective! <br>
